      {
        "content": "DigitalWellbeing: Social media needs mental health reforms\n\nSocial media platforms often prioritize engagement and profit over user well-being, leading to addictive usage patterns, cyberbullying, and the spread of harmful content. Algorithms are designed to maximize screen time, fostering environments that can exacerbate anxiety, depression, and loneliness, particularly among young users. While social media provides opportunities for connection, it simultaneously subjects individuals to unrealistic standards and constant comparison, damaging self-esteem and mental health. Reform is necessary to implement features that promote balanced usage, provide mental health resources, and ensure safe online spaces. Without these changes, social media will continue to harm its users' mental health.",
